Load Libraries

library(readxl)
library(here)
library(tidyverse)
library(ggplot2)
library(knitr)

Load and clean data

df <- read_excel(here("data", 
                      "plant", 
                      "SF1_GC_data.xlsx"),
                 sheet = "germination")

Percent Germinated

#Percent germinated at experiment end

df.mean <- df %>%
  filter(day_number==28) %>%
  group_by(soil, oil) %>% 
  summarise(perc_germ = (12-not_germinated) / 12) %>% 
  group_by(soil, oil) %>%
  summarise(mean_perc_germ = mean(perc_germ),
            sd = sd(perc_germ),
            se = sd(perc_germ)/sqrt(n()))
## `summarise()` regrouping output by 'soil', 'oil' (override with `.groups` argument)
## `summarise()` regrouping output by 'soil' (override with `.groups` argument)
kable(df.mean)
soil oil mean_perc_germ sd se
L N 0.3263889 0.1254202 0.0362057
L Y 0.3888889 0.1247894 0.0360236
S N 0.2152778 0.1351128 0.0390037
S Y 0.2361111 0.1368538 0.0395063 
df.mean %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = soil,
           y = mean_perc_germ,
           fill = oil)) +
  geom_col() +
  geom_errorbar(aes(ymin = mean_perc_germ-2*se,
                    ymax = mean_perc_germ+2*se),
                width = 0.2) +
  facet_wrap(~ oil)

Stats on percent germinated

The idea here is to get a percentage of seeds germinated from each pot and then treat those as continuous variables. I think this is ok as long as the variance is equal. See this discussion

df.perc <- df %>%
  filter(day_number==28) %>%
  group_by(soil, oil) %>% 
  summarise(perc_germ = (12-not_germinated) / 12) 
## `summarise()` regrouping output by 'soil', 'oil' (override with `.groups` argument)
M <- lm(perc_germ ~ soil*oil, data = df.perc)

Check heteroscedasticity and normality

df %>%
  filter(day_number==28) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = soil,
           y = 12-not_germinated,
           color = oil)) +
  geom_boxplot()

Looks reasonable to me.

Germination Rate

M <- glm(perc_germ ~ soil*oil, family = quasibinomial, 
         weights = rep(12, nrow(df.perc)),
          data = df.perc)

#Adding weights doesn't seem to make a diference in results.

Whether soil was autoclaved or not is barely significant. I have a feeling if I remove the two replicates that didn’t germinate any seeds, this will disappear.

df.perc.no.zero <- df.perc %>% 
  filter(perc_germ!=0)

M <- glm(perc_germ ~ soil*oil, family = quasibinomial,
          data = df.perc.no.zero)

summary(M)

Plot of LOESS smoothing on germination

Nice explanation of how LOESS smoothing works.

ggplot(data = df,
       aes(x = day_number,
           y = 12 - not_germinated,
           shape = factor(oil),
           color = factor(soil))) +
  geom_jitter() +
  geom_smooth() +
  theme_bw()
## `geom_smooth()` using method = 'loess' and formula 'y ~ x'
